SOURCEDETAIL: ILOSTAT, indicator Female share of employment in senior and middle management (%). Available at www.ilo.org/ilostat -> Browse by subject -> Yearly indicators -> Employment. For the specific sources by country, refer to the table in ILOSTAT directly.
FOOTNOTES: The female share of employment in senior and middle management refers to major group 1 (managers) in both ISCO-08 and ISCO-88 minus category 14 in ISCO-08 (hospitality, retail and other services managers) and minus category 13 in ISCO-88 (general managers), since these comprise mainly managers of small enterprises. It's an ILOSTAT calculated indicator, based on data submitted by each country on employment by sex and occupation.

Changes in the definition of birth registration were made from the second and third rounds of MICS (MICS2 and MICS3) to the fourth round (MICS4). In order to allow for comparability with later rounds, data from MICS2 and MICS3 on birth registration were recalculated according to the MICS4 indicator definition. Therefore, the recalculated data presented here may differ from estimates included in MICS2 and MICS3 national reports.  Estimates of 100% were assumed given that civil registration systems in these countries are complete and all vital events (including births) are registered. SOURCEDETAIL: The figures included here concern only cases of killing of journalists and associated media personnel. UNESCO does not collect data on trade unionists and human rights advocates, nor does it collect data on the number of cases of kidnapping, enforced disappearance, arbitrary detention or torture of journalists and associated media personnel.
FOOTNOTES: Killings of journalists, associated media personnel and bloggers condemned by the UNESCO Director-General through press releases published on the UNESCO website. Member States are annually requested to provide to UNESCO an update on the status of the judicial enquiries into these cases. On the basis of the information provided by Member States, the Director-General of UNESCO presents a biennial Report on the Safety of Journalists and the Danger of Impunity to the Intergovernmental Council of the International Programme for the Development of Communication (IPDC). Every other year, a chapter on the safety of journlaists is included in the World Trends in Freedom of Expression and Media Development Report.
